The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — This summer, readers around the world held celebrations marking the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Sorcerer’s Stone in the United States). They had ample reason to celebrate.
Since the young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "boy who lived" has become a "symbol of resilience and perseverance."
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, translated into over 70 languages, and has sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
The eight films based on this book have earned a cumulative $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated another $7 billion in revenue.
It is hard to imagine, for those of a certain age and with a literary mindset, a day when the global audience was not captivated by Rowling's works.
Therefore, I am always amazed when I recall my students' poor reaction to the book Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in the fall of 1999, when I included it in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching a "Bestselling American Books" course since 1993.
This course examines popular works from the 17th century up to the present, inviting students to reflect on why and how these bestsellers have attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask students to choose a final book that represents popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the Pottermania swept across the American coast.
In June, the American publisher of the series urgently released the second book of the Harry Potter series, Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets, in hardcover to bookstores.
The publisher also released the third book of the series, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, on September 8, as well as the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone.
By the end of that month, Rowling's novels had claimed the top three spots on the New York Times Bestseller list, with the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone taking the number one position on the paperback bestseller list.
Time magazine even featured the bespectacled wizard on its cover.
Harry Potter's image is everywhere you look.
My students are eager to know why there is such fervor.
Oh dear, they are utterly disappointed.
In their eyes, the Harry Potter series is nothing more than second-rate nonsense, far below the cherished series they remember from their childhood, such as The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings.
Although their childhoods are only a few years behind them, they criticize Harry Potter just like many notorious adult critics: "contrived," "poor writing," "clichéd," and "boring."

In their view, Harry has neither miracles, nor wisdom, nor warmth.
The students' dislike surprised me, but in retrospect, it was nothing to be surprised about.
Although adults have always formed a large part of the audience for Harry Potter, these students were exactly in the wrong age group to view the Harry Potter phenomenon objectively.
They were past the age of accepting new children's literature, but at the same time too young to have their own children (I had just become a parent at that time), and they eagerly insisted that although the Harry Potter series was now very popular, it would soon be forgotten.
In the fall of the next year, which was 2000, the next batch of students also chose *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone* as the final analysis text, just like their predecessors, confidently refusing to accept the work.
Let's fast forward to spring of 2007.
After putting the course on hold for several years, I taught "Bestselling American Books" again.
When the students chose the final analysis text, they selected *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone*.
And I was ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who were not college students when they first read Rowling's works, but rather teenagers in their early teens, just beginning to enter adolescence. This means they grew up together with Harry, Ron, and Hermione into young adulthood.
The same thing happened again in the fall of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, rather than just a label.
Will Harry disappear from memory?
It's impossible as long as we are alive.
I have taught the bestselling books course twice since 2010, and in both cases, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final commentary.
Are you tired of Potter?
This seems unlikely based on the reviews received for the Harry Potter series in my other course on children's literature, where I teach Rowling's works.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not choose *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone*, instead selecting *Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban* — this is my favorite of the seven Harry Potter novels, marking the transition of the series from children's literature to young adult fiction. The book offers a complex portrayal of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also favorite this book.
But how long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I conduct a survey first: "Which books in the reading list did you read as a child?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban."
In 2012, this number rose to 94%.
But the percentage continued to decline in the following years — 87% in 2014, and dropped to 81% in 2016.
These are not scientific figures, I know.
But I’m curious: when I teach "Children’s Literature" again next spring, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter’s status is constantly declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Or is there a balance point ahead, where the percentage can stabilize and stop declining?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I am glad to have invited him into my classroom.
